  <H1>FitzHugh-Nagumo Model: Reduced Excitable Dynamics</H1>

  <Body>The Hodgkin-Huxley model provides a remarkably accurate description of action potential generation, but its four-dimensional state space makes geometric analysis challenging. In this lesson, we explore the FitzHugh-Nagumo (FHN) model—a two-dimensional reduction that captures the essential features of neuronal excitability while enabling powerful phase plane analysis. This reduction reveals the geometric structure underlying threshold behavior, excitability, and the transition to oscillations.</Body>

  <H2>From Hodgkin-Huxley to FitzHugh-Nagumo</H2>

  <Body>Richard FitzHugh (1961) and Jin-ichi Nagumo (1962) independently developed reduced models that preserve the qualitative dynamics of excitable membranes. The key insight is that the HH model's four variables operate on different timescales: the voltage V and sodium activation m are fast, while sodium inactivation h and potassium activation n are slow. Moreover, h and n are approximately linearly related during an action potential.</Body>

  <Body>The FitzHugh-Nagumo model collapses these dynamics into two variables:</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
dv/dt = K[-v(v - α)(v - 1) - w] + I
dw/dt = b(v - cw)
  </Code>

  <Body>Here, v represents a dimensionless voltage-like variable (the "excitation" variable), and w is a "recovery" variable that combines the effects of sodium inactivation and potassium activation. The parameter α sets the threshold, K controls the timescale of the fast dynamics, I is the external input current, b determines the timescale of the slow recovery, and c affects the slope of the w-nullcline.</Body>

  <FlashCard id="fc1">
    <Front>What does the variable v represent in the FitzHugh-Nagumo model?</Front>
    <Back>The variable v is a dimensionless excitation variable representing membrane voltage. It is the fast variable that exhibits threshold behavior and action potential-like dynamics.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <FlashCard id="fc2">
    <Front>What does the recovery variable w represent in the FitzHugh-Nagumo model?</Front>
    <Back>The recovery variable w combines the effects of sodium inactivation (h) and potassium activation (n) from the Hodgkin-Huxley model. It acts as a slow negative feedback that terminates excitation and produces refractoriness.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <H2>Nullcline Analysis</H2>

  <Body>The power of the FHN model lies in its amenability to phase plane analysis. A nullcline is the set of points where one variable's time derivative equals zero. For the FHN system:</Body>

  <Body>The v-nullcline (where dv/dt = 0) is given by:</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
w = -v(v - α)(v - 1) + I/K
  </Code>

  <Body>This is a cubic function of v, creating an N-shaped (or inverted N-shaped) curve in the phase plane. The shape of this cubic is crucial for excitability—it creates the threshold behavior characteristic of neurons.</Body>

  <Body>The w-nullcline (where dw/dt = 0) is simply:</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
w = v/c
  </Code>

  <Body>This is a straight line through the origin with slope 1/c. The fixed points of the system occur where the nullclines intersect.</Body>

  <FlashCard id="fc3">
    <Front>What is a nullcline?</Front>
    <Back>A nullcline is the set of all points in phase space where one particular variable's time derivative equals zero. For a 2D system with variables (x, y), the x-nullcline satisfies dx/dt = 0, and the y-nullcline satisfies dy/dt = 0.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <Body>Here is Python code for plotting the FHN nullclines:</Body>

  <Code lang="python">
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_fhn_nullclines(alpha=0.1, K=1.0, I=0.0, c=3.0, b=0.01):
    """Plot FitzHugh-Nagumo nullclines."""
    v = np.linspace(-0.5, 1.5, 500)

    # v-nullcline: w = -v(v - alpha)(v - 1) + I/K
    w_vnull = -v * (v - alpha) * (v - 1) + I/K

    # w-nullcline: w = v/c
    w_wnull = v / c

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.plot(v, w_vnull, 'b-', linewidth=2, label='v-nullcline (dv/dt = 0)')
    plt.plot(v, w_wnull, 'r-', linewidth=2, label='w-nullcline (dw/dt = 0)')

    # Find approximate intersection (fixed point)
    idx = np.argmin(np.abs(w_vnull - w_wnull))
    plt.plot(v[idx], w_vnull[idx], 'ko', markersize=10, label='Fixed point')

    plt.xlabel('v (excitation)', fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('w (recovery)', fontsize=12)
    plt.title('FitzHugh-Nagumo Nullclines', fontsize=14)
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    plt.xlim(-0.5, 1.5)
    plt.ylim(-0.1, 0.3)
    plt.show()

    return v[idx], w_vnull[idx]

v_fp, w_fp = plot_fhn_nullclines()
print(f"Fixed point: (v*, w*) ≈ ({v_fp:.3f}, {w_fp:.3f})")
  </Code>

