  <H2>Fixed Point Stability and Linearization</H2>

  <Body>To determine the stability of a fixed point (v*, w*), we linearize the system by computing the Jacobian matrix:</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
J = | ∂f/∂v   ∂f/∂w |   =   | K[-3v² + 2(α+1)v - α]   -K |
    | ∂g/∂v   ∂g/∂w |       |          b              -bc |
  </Code>

  <Body>where f(v,w) = K[-v(v-α)(v-1) - w] + I and g(v,w) = b(v - cw). Evaluated at the fixed point, the eigenvalues of J determine stability:</Body>

  <Body>• If both eigenvalues have negative real parts → stable node or spiral (the system returns to the fixed point after perturbation)</Body>
  <Body>• If both eigenvalues have positive real parts → unstable node or spiral</Body>
  <Body>• If eigenvalues are complex conjugates with negative real part → stable spiral (damped oscillations)</Body>
  <Body>• If eigenvalues cross the imaginary axis → Hopf bifurcation occurs</Body>

  <Code lang="python">
import numpy as np

def fhn_jacobian(v, w, alpha=0.1, K=1.0, c=3.0, b=0.01):
    """Compute Jacobian of FHN system at point (v, w)."""
    # df/dv = K * [-3v^2 + 2(alpha + 1)v - alpha]
    df_dv = K * (-3*v**2 + 2*(alpha + 1)*v - alpha)
    df_dw = -K
    dg_dv = b
    dg_dw = -b * c

    return np.array([[df_dv, df_dw],
                     [dg_dv, dg_dw]])

def analyze_stability(v_star, w_star, alpha=0.1, K=1.0, c=3.0, b=0.01):
    """Analyze stability of fixed point via eigenvalues."""
    J = fhn_jacobian(v_star, w_star, alpha, K, c, b)
    eigenvalues = np.linalg.eigvals(J)

    print(f"Jacobian at fixed point ({v_star:.3f}, {w_star:.3f}):")
    print(J)
    print(f"\nEigenvalues: {eigenvalues}")

    # Classify stability
    real_parts = np.real(eigenvalues)
    imag_parts = np.imag(eigenvalues)

    if np.all(real_parts &lt; 0):
        if np.any(imag_parts != 0):
            stability = "Stable spiral (damped oscillations)"
        else:
            stability = "Stable node"
    elif np.all(real_parts &gt; 0):
        if np.any(imag_parts != 0):
            stability = "Unstable spiral"
        else:
            stability = "Unstable node"
    else:
        stability = "Saddle point"

    print(f"Stability: {stability}")
    return eigenvalues, stability

# Example: analyze stability at a typical fixed point
eigenvalues, stability = analyze_stability(0.0, 0.0)
  </Code>

