  <H2>Timescale Separation and the Recovery Variable</H2>

  <Body>A crucial feature of the FHN model is the separation of timescales between v and w. The parameter b controls the rate of the recovery dynamics—when b is small (b ≪ K), the recovery variable w changes much more slowly than the excitation variable v.</Body>

  <Body>This timescale separation has important consequences:</Body>
  <Body>• During excitation: v changes rapidly while w remains nearly constant (fast subsystem)</Body>
  <Body>• During recovery: w slowly increases, eventually allowing v to return to rest</Body>
  <Body>• The slow recovery creates the refractory period—a second stimulus cannot trigger a full response until w has decreased sufficiently</Body>

  <Code lang="python">
def illustrate_timescale_separation():
    """Show how different b values affect dynamics."""
    alpha, K, I, c = 0.1, 1.0, 0.0, 3.0
    b_values = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1]  # Different recovery timescales

    t = np.linspace(0, 300, 3000)

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 4))

    for ax, b in zip(axes, b_values):
        # Start with suprathreshold perturbation
        initial = [0.3, 0.0]
        solution = odeint(fhn_system, initial, t, args=(alpha, K, I, c, b))

        ax.plot(t, solution[:, 0], 'b-', label='v (excitation)')
        ax.plot(t, solution[:, 1], 'r-', label='w (recovery)')
        ax.set_xlabel('Time')
        ax.set_ylabel('Variable value')
        ax.set_title(f'b = {b} (τ_w/τ_v ≈ {1/b:.0f})')
        ax.legend()
        ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)

    plt.suptitle('Effect of Recovery Timescale (b) on FHN Dynamics', fontsize=14)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

illustrate_timescale_separation()
