  <H2>Summary</H2>

  <Body>The FitzHugh-Nagumo model is a powerful tool for understanding neuronal excitability. By reducing the four-dimensional Hodgkin-Huxley system to two dimensions, it reveals the geometric essence of threshold behavior, refractory periods, and the transition between excitable and oscillatory regimes. The model's tractability makes it invaluable for theoretical analysis, while its qualitative accuracy ensures biological relevance.</Body>

  <Body>Key takeaways:</Body>
  <Body>1. The FHN model captures essential excitability with just two variables (v and w)</Body>
  <Body>2. Nullcline analysis reveals fixed points and their stability</Body>
  <Body>3. Timescale separation between fast excitation and slow recovery underlies the action potential</Body>
  <Body>4. Hopf bifurcations mark the transition from excitable to oscillatory behavior</Body>
  <Body>5. Phase plane geometry provides intuition for threshold behavior and refractoriness</Body>

